===Sewing machine brand===
[[Aisin]], another member of the [[Toyota Group]] of companies, uses the same Toyota wordmark logo to market its home-use [[sewing machine]]s. Aisin was founded by [[Kiichiro Toyoda]] after he founded the Toyota Motor Corporation. According to Aisin, he was so pleased with the first sewing machine, he decided to apply the same Toyota branding as his auto business, despite the companies being independent from each other.<ref>{{Cite web |title=History of TOYOTA home-use sewing machine |url=http://www.aisin.co.jp/life/fashion/history/index.html |access-date=July 21, 2021 |website=www.aisin.co.jp |archive-date=July 21, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210721231831/http://www.aisin.co.jp/life/fashion/history/index.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Carbon removal===
{{Further|Carbon capture and utilization|Carbon footprint|Electrochemical reduction of carbon dioxide|Heterogeneous catalysis}}

Toyota Ventures, along with [[JetBlue]] Technology Ventures and [[Parley for the Oceans]], is among the corporate investors that have invested $40 million in the [[Air Company]], a [[Carbon footprint|carbon negative]] [[vodka]] [[Liquor|distiller]] and [[perfume]] and [[hand sanitizer]] manufacturer that uses [[heterogeneous catalysis]] to [[Carbon capture and utilization|convert captured carbon]] into [[ethanol]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Olick|first=Diana|date=May 16, 2022|title=This start-up makes vodka out of CO2 emissions, and it's backed by Toyota and JetBlue|publisher=[[CNBC]]|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/05/16/air-company-makes-vodka-out-of-co2-emissions-backed-by-toyota-jetblue.html|access-date=August 3, 2022}}</ref>

===Environmental initiatives===

Toyota states it is committed to achieving carbon neutrality by 2050, and it has set a goal to reduce its overall carbon emissions by 90% by 2050, compared to 2010 levels.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shrestha |first=Priyanka |date=April 20, 2021 |title=Toyota aims to become carbon-neutral by 2050 |url=https://www.futurenetzero.com/2021/04/20/toyota-aims-to-become-carbon-neutral-by-2050/ |access-date=June 24, 2023 |website=future Net Zero |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Indiablooms |title=Toyota Kirloskar Motor takes giant strides towards achieving Zero Carbon Emission manufacturing facility {{!}} Indiablooms – First Portal on Digital News Management |url=https://www.indiablooms.com/finance-details/9871/toyota-kirloskar-motor-takes-giant-strides-towards-achieving-zero-carbon-emission-manufacturing-facility.html |access-date=April 11, 2023 |website=Indiablooms.com |language=en}}</ref>

The company has invested heavily in solar energy, with a goal to install solar panels on the rooftops of all its dealerships worldwide by 2050.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sylvia |first=Eric Wesoff and Tim |date=August 13, 2020 |title=Morning Brief: wind and solar continue to rise drastically in the global power mix, Toyota announces three new solar projects |url=https://pv-magazine-usa.com/2020/08/13/morning-brief-wind-and-solar-continue-to-rise-drastically-in-the-global-power-mix-toyota-announces-three-new-solar-projects/ |access-date=March 7, 2023 |website=pv magazine USA |language=en-US}}</ref> In addition, Toyota has partnered with various renewable energy companies to promote the use of wind and solar power, including a recent partnership with ENEOS Corporation to develop hydrogen refueling stations in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bellan |first=Rebecca |date=May 11, 2021 |title=Toyota partners with ENEOS to explore a hydrogen-powered Woven City |url=https://techcrunch.com/2021/05/10/toyota-partners-with-eneos-to-explore-a-hydrogen-powered-woven-city/ |access-date=April 11, 2023 |website=[[TechCrunch]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

Toyota has launched a program called "Global Environmental Challenge" 2050 which is a comprehensive initiative aimed at reducing the environmental impact of Toyota's operations. The challenge includes six environmental goals that Toyota aims to achieve by 2050, including reducing carbon emissions, minimizing water usage, promoting the recycling and reuse of materials, and promoting the use of renewable energy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hardcastle |first=Jessica Lyons |date=October 19, 2015 |title=Toyota aims for zero carbon emissions over life of a vehicle |url=https://www.environmentalleader.com/2015/10/toyota-targets-zero-carbon-emissions-from-vehicle-lifecycle-plants-by-2050/ |access-date=April 11, 2023 |website=Environment + Energy Leader |language=en-US}}</ref> The company has also implemented a variety of initiatives to promote sustainability across its supply chain, including efforts to reduce waste, water usage, and promote sustainable agriculture. For example, Toyota has implemented a [[Zero waste|zero-waste]] initiative at its manufacturing plants, aiming to send zero waste to landfills.<ref>{{Cite web |title=StackPath |url=https://www.industryweek.com/the-economy/environment/article/21943034/toyotas-zero-landfill-factory |access-date=March 7, 2023 |website=www.industryweek.com}}</ref>

==Controversies==
=== Corrosion lawsuit ===
In November 2016, Toyota agreed to pay $3.4 billion to settle allegations that roughly one-and-a-half million of its Tacoma, Tundra, and Sequoia pickup trucks and SUVs had been outfitted with frames prone to corrosion and perforation. According to court papers, the corrosion could reach levels high enough to compromise the vehicle's structural integrity.<ref>{{Cite news|date=November 12, 2016|title=Toyota to settle U.S. truck rust lawsuit for up to $3.4 billion|language=en|work=[[Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toyota-settlement-idUSKBN1370PE|access-date=February 21, 2022}}</ref>

=== Death from overwork ===
{{See also|Karōshi}}

On February 9, 2002, Kenichi Uchino, aged 30 years, a quality control manager, collapsed then died at work.<ref name="karoshi" /><ref>{{Cite news |date=December 1, 2007 |title=Nagoya court rules Toyota employee died from overwork |work=The Japan Times |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2007/12/01/national/nagoya-court-rules-toyota-employee-died-from-overwork/ |url-status=live |access-date=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211071609/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2007/12/01/national/nagoya-court-rules-toyota-employee-died-from-overwork/ |archive-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> On January 2, 2006, an unnamed chief engineer of the [[Toyota Camry|Camry Hybrid]], aged 45 years, died from [[heart failure]] in his bed.<ref name="karoshi">{{Cite news |last=Harden |first=Blaine |date=July 13, 2008 |title=Japan's Killer Work Ethic |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] Foreign Service |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/12/AR2008071201630.html |url-status=live |access-date=June 29, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615213814/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/12/AR2008071201630.html |archive-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref>

===Fines for environmental breaches{{anchor|fines}}===
In 2003, Toyota was fined $34 million for violating the [[United States Clean Air Act]], as 2.2 million vehicles it sold had defective smog-control computers.<ref name="fs-2010-02-11">{{Cite news |last=Mattera |first=Phil |date=February 11, 2010 |title=Toyota totals its corporate social responsibility cred |work=Facing South |location=US |url=https://www.facingsouth.org/2010/02/toyota-totals-its-corporate-social-responsibility-cred.html |access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref>

In January 2021, Toyota was fined $180 million for delays in reporting emissions-related defects to the [[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) between 2005 and 2015.<ref name="The New York Times 2021">{{Cite news |last=Tabuchi |first=Hiroko |date=January 14, 2021 |title=Toyota to Pay a Record Fine for a Decade of Clean Air Act Violations |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/14/climate/toyota-emissions-fine.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114205251/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/14/climate/toyota-emissions-fine.html |archive-date=January 14, 2021 |url-access=limited |access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref><ref name="wsj-2021-01-14">{{Cite news |last=Prang |first=Allison |date=January 14, 2021 |title=Toyota to Pay $180 Million to Settle Complaint Over Delayed Emissions Defect Reports |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|location=US |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/toyota-to-pay-180-million-to-settle-complaint-over-delayed-emissions-defect-reports-11610653555 |access-date=January 15, 2021}}</ref><ref name="dn-2021-01-14">{{Cite news |date=January 14, 2021 |title=Toyota to pay $180 million fine for failing to report and fix pollution control defects |agency=[[Associated Press]] |location=US |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/business/autos/2021/01/14/toyota-to-pay-180-million-fine-for-failing-to-fix-pollution-control-defects/ |access-date=January 15, 2021 |via=Dallas News}}</ref> The acting U.S. attorney said that the delays "likely led to delayed or avoided emissions-related recalls", although Toyota stated that despite the delays in reporting the issues to the EPA, it had notified customers and fixed the cars with the emissions defects.<ref name="dn-2021-01-14" /> At the time, this was the biggest civil penalty ever levied for violating the EPA's emission reporting requirements.<ref name="The New York Times 2021" /><ref name="wsj-2021-01-14" />

=== 2009–2011 unintended acceleration recalls ===
{{See also|2009–2011 Toyota vehicle recalls}}

Between 2009 and 2011 Toyota, under pressure from the U.S. [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA), conducted recalls of millions of vehicles after reports that several drivers experienced [[Sudden unintended acceleration|unintended acceleration]]. The first recall, in November 2009, was to prevent a front driver's side [[Car mat|floor mat]] from sliding into the [[Automobile pedal|foot pedal]] well, causing the pedals to become trapped. The second recall, in January 2010, was begun after some crashes were shown not to have been caused by floor mats and may be caused by possible mechanical sticking of the [[accelerator pedal]].<ref name="pressroom.toyota.com">{{Cite press release |title=Amended Recall: Potential Floor Mat Interference with Accelerator Pedal |date=September 29, 2009 |publisher=Toyota |url=http://pressroom.toyota.com/pr/tms/toyota/toyota-consumer-safety-advisory-102572.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221013729/http://pressroom.toyota.com/pr/tms/toyota/toyota-consumer-safety-advisory-102572.aspx |archive-date=December 21, 2009}}</ref> Worldwide, approximately 9 million cars and trucks were impacted by the recalls.<ref name="CSM">{{Cite news |last=Haq |first=Husna |date=January 29, 2010 |title=Toyota recall update: dealers face full lots, anxious customers |work=The Christian Science Monitor |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2010/0129/Toyota-recall-update-dealers-face-full-lots-anxious-customers |url-status=live |access-date=January 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202035132/http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/2010/0129/Toyota-recall-update-dealers-face-full-lots-anxious-customers |archive-date=February 2, 2010}}</ref>

NHTSA received reports of a total of 37 deaths allegedly related to unintended acceleration, although an exact number was never verified.<ref name="Healey 2010">{{Cite news |last=Healey |first=James R. |date=February 17, 2010 |title=Toyota deaths reported to safety database rise to 37 |work=[[USA Today]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/autos/2010-02-17-toyota17_ST_N.htm |access-date=February 11, 2011}}</ref> As a result of the problems, Toyota faced nearly 100 lawsuits from the families of those killed, drivers who were injured, vehicle owners who lost resale value, and investors who saw a drop in the value of their shares. While most of the personal injury and wrongful death lawsuits were settled confidentially,<ref name="Hirsch 2013">{{Cite news |last1=Hirsch |first1=Jerry |last2=Bensinger |first2=Ken |date=October 25, 2013 |title=Toyota settles acceleration lawsuit after $3-million verdict |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/oct/25/autos/la-fi-hy-toyota-damages-20131026 |access-date=November 24, 2013}}</ref> Toyota did spend more than {{USD|1 billion}} to settle a class action lawsuit to compensate owners for lost resale value,<ref name="Zalubowski 2012">{{Cite news |last=Zalubowski |first=David |date=December 26, 2012 |title=Toyota settlement in sudden-acceleration case will top $1 billion |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-toyota-to-pay-at-least-12-billion-to-settle-suddenacceleration-lawsuit-20121226,0,7432292.story |access-date=December 27, 2012}}</ref> and the company agreed to pay a {{USD|1.2 billion}} criminal penalty to the United States government over accusations that it had intentionally hid information about safety defects from the public and had made deceptive statements to protect its brand image. The penalty was the largest ever levied against a car company.<ref name="fined2">{{Cite news |last1=Vlasic |first1=Bill |last2=Apuzzo |first2=Matt |date=March 19, 2014 |title=Toyota Is Fined $1.2 Billion for Concealing Safety Defects |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/20/business/toyota-reaches-1-2-billion-settlement-in-criminal-inquiry.html |access-date=March 20, 2014}}</ref>

=== Takata airbag recalls ===
{{See also|Takata airbag recalls}}

Toyota was impacted by a recall of faulty airbag inflators made by Takata. The inflators can explode, shooting metal fragments into the vehicle cabin. Millions of vehicles produced between 2000 and 2014 were impacted by the recall, with some needing multiple repairs.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Atiyeh |first=Clifford |date=November 13, 2014 |title=Massive Takata Airbag Recall: Everything You Need to Know, Including Full List of Affected Vehicles |work=Car and Driver |url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/massive-takata-airbag-recall-everything-you-need-to-know-including-full-list-of-affected-vehicles |url-status=live |access-date=November 15, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129064936/http://blog.caranddriver.com/massive-takata-airbag-recall-everything-you-need-to-know-including-full-list-of-affected-vehicles/ |archive-date=November 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=December 12, 2018 |title=Toyota advances plans to replace Takata airbags in 65,000 vehicles |work=[[Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toyota-takata/toyota-advances-plans-to-replace-takata-airbags-in-65000-vehicles-idUSKBN1OB2IO |url-status=live |access-date=December 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181212200454/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-toyota-takata/toyota-advances-plans-to-replace-takata-airbags-in-65000-vehicles-idUSKBN1OB2IO |archive-date=December 12, 2018}}</ref>

=== June 2010 Chinese labour strike ===
On June 21, 2010, a [[2010 Chinese labour unrest#Honda|Chinese labor strike]] happened in Tianjin Toyoda Gosei Co, Tianjin. Workers demanded better wages and treatment.<ref name="21june2010strike">{{Cite web |date=June 23, 2010 |title=Strike halts production at Denso plant in China |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2010/06/23/business/strike-halts-production-at-denso-plant-in-china/#.WU_imDDasUo |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180211080102/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2010/06/23/business/strike-halts-production-at-denso-plant-in-china/#.WU_imDDasUo |archive-date=February 11, 2018 |access-date=June 25, 2017}}</ref>

=== Extremist usage ===
In 2015, U.S. officials asked Toyota how the [[Islamic State]] was in possession of so many Toyota trucks.<ref>{{Cite web |title=US Officials Ask How ISIS Got So Many Toyota Trucks |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/us-officials-isis-toyota-trucks/story?id=34266539 |access-date=August 3, 2023 |website=ABC News |language=en}}</ref> Toyota cars have also been documented to have been used by other extremist organizations such as the [[Taliban]], [[Hamas]], [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-shabab]] and [[Piracy off the coast of Somalia|Somali pirates]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Islamic State and others using Toyota trucks |url=https://www.beaumontenterprise.com/news/slideshow/Islamic-State-and-others-using-Toyota-trucks-118278.php |access-date=August 3, 2023 |archive-date=August 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230803141320/https://www.beaumontenterprise.com/news/slideshow/Islamic-State-and-others-using-Toyota-trucks-118278.php |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Somaiya |first=Ravi |date=October 14, 2010 |title=Why Rebel Groups Love the Toyota Hilux |url=https://www.newsweek.com/why-rebel-groups-love-toyota-hilux-74195 |access-date=August 3, 2023 |website=Newsweek |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=May 8, 2009 |title=For Somali Pirates, Worst Enemy May Be on Shore (Published 2009) |work=The New York Times |language=en |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/09/world/africa/09pirate.html |access-date=August 3, 2023 |last1=Gettleman |first1=Jeffrey }}</ref> Toyota representatives have said the company has a strict policy of to not sell vehicles to potential purchasers who may use or modify them for paramilitary or terrorist activities and that it cannot track aftermarket sales and that it has worked with the [[United States Department of the Treasury|U.S Treasury]] to brief them on Toyota's supply chain on the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Engel |first=Pamela |title=These Toyota trucks are popular with terrorists — here's why |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/why-isis-uses-toyota-trucks-2015-10 |access-date=August 3, 2023 |website=Business Insider |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Misleading marketing ===
In its marketing, Toyota has often referred to its non-plug-in hybrid vehicles as "self-charging hybrid" vehicles. The use of the term has caused some criticism that this is misleading, as some consumers were led to erroneously believe that these vehicles charge their batteries on their own when the vehicles are not used.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 27, 2020 |title=Toyta's self-charging hybrid ads deemed misleading, banned in Norway |url=https://insideevs.com/news/395138/toyota-self-charging-ads-banned-norway/ |website=www.insideevs.com |publisher=InsideEVs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=October 24, 2020 |title=Don't' fall for the self-charging hybrid con |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamesmorris/2020/10/24/dont-fall-for-the-self-charging-hybrid-con/?sh=7192a5f3119f |website=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> Complaints about self-charging hybrid advertising were recorded in Ireland, although the complaints were rejected by the Advertising Standards Authority of Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 5, 2019 |title=Toyota hybrid falls foul of ad rules after misleading cost saving claim |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/toyota-hybrid-falls-foul-of-ad-rules-after-misleading-cost-saving-claim-4796800-Sep2019/ |website=www.journal.ie |publisher=The Journal}}</ref> However, in 2020, the Norwegian Consumer Authority banned the adverts outright in Norway, stating: "It is misleading to give the impression that the power to the hybrid battery is free of charge, since the electricity produced by the car has consumption of gasoline as a necessary condition."<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 24, 2020 |title=Toyota's self-charging hybrid ad banned by this country |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/toyotas-self-charging-hybrid-ad-banned-country-2909041 |website=www.ibtimes.com |publisher=International Business Times}}</ref>

Electric vehicle website [[IrishEVs]] criticised Toyota Ireland for paying [[University College Dublin]] to conduct a study of only seven examples of their hybrid cars over seven days to make a press release about the efficiency of the vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 29, 2021 |title=Claims about environmental benefits of hybrid vehicles 'greenwashing' |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/motoring/arid-40300817.html |website=www.irishexaminer.com |publisher=Irish Examiner}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 29, 2021 |title=Irish Examiner view: Verification has huge role in climate wars |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/opinion/ourview/arid-40301414.html |website=www.irishexaminer.com |publisher=Irish Examiner}}</ref> The website also criticised Toyota Ireland for using opinion polls to substantiate a claim about their {{CO2}} emissions on Twitter.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 25, 2021 |title=We Need To Talk About Toyota |url=https://www.irishevs.com/we-need-to-talk-about-toyota |website=www.irishevs.com |publisher=IrishEVs}}</ref>

=== Safety-related misconduct by Daihatsu===
In April 2023, it was revealed that Toyota subsidiary Daihatsu had cheated by rigging some models to perform better in crash tests than actual production cars. The vehicles in question had a notch in the interior panel of the front door which avoided the possibility of the collision creating a sharp edge that could have injured an occupant when the side airbag deployed. This notch was present on the tested vehicles but not on vehicles sold to the public.<ref name="Motor1-2023-04-28">{{cite news |url=https://www.motor1.com/news/664748/toyota-admits-daihatsu-side-crash-tests-rigged/ |title=Toyota Admits Some Daihatsu Crash Test Cars Were Rigged For Better Results |first1=Chris |last1=Bruce |work=Motor1 |date=April 28, 2023 |access-date=May 16, 2023}}</ref>

The issue affected four models, the [[Toyota Yaris Ativ (AC100)|Toyota Yaris Ativ]] (also known as the Vios), [[Perodua Axia]], [[Toyota Agya]], and an undisclosed upcoming product. No recall was conducted over the issue.<ref name="Motor1-2023-04-28"/>

In December 2023, Daihatsu halted shipments of 64 models, including two dozens branded as Toyota, after safety investigations uncovered misconduct far greater in scope than previously expected. In some models, the test speeds and results of [[Head restraint|headrest]] impact tests were falsified. In models such as the [[Toyota TownAce|TownAce]] and [[Toyota Pixis Joy|Pixis Joy]], the [[airbag]] control unit used in testing was different from the part installed on vehicles sold to the public. Affected markets included Japan as well as Bolivia, Cambodia, Chile, Ecuador, Indonesia, Malaysia, Mexico, Peru, Thailand, Uruguay, and Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Leussink |first=Daniel |date=20 December 2023 |title=Toyota's Daihatsu to halt all vehicle shipments, in widening safety scandal |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/toyotas-daihatsu-will-expand-production-halt-over-safety-scandal-nikkei-2023-12-20/}}</ref>

==Corporate affairs==
[[File:Headquarter of Toyota Motor Corporation 4.JPG|thumb|Principal headquarters building of Toyota]]

Toyota is headquartered in the city of [[Toyota, Aichi|Toyota]],<ref name="Toyotaprofile">{{Cite web |date=March 31, 2014 |title=Overview |url=http://www.toyota-global.com/company/profile/overview/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213041727/http://www.toyota-global.com/company/profile/overview/ |archive-date=February 13, 2015 |access-date=February 6, 2015 |website=Global website |publisher=Toyota Motor Corporation}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2023}} which was named Koromo until 1951, when it changed its name to match the automaker. Toyota City is located in the [[Aichi Prefecture]] of Japan. The main headquarters of Toyota is located in a four-story building that has been described as "modest".<ref name="Jacob">{{Cite news |last=Jacob |first=Vinod |date=August 18, 2006 |title=In Toyota land |work=[[The Hindu]] – [[Business Line]] |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2006/08/18/stories/2006081800020200.htm |url-status=dead |access-date=May 9, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100721173402/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/life/2006/08/18/stories/2006081800020200.htm |archive-date=July 21, 2010}}</ref> In 2013, company CEO Akio Toyoda reported that it had difficulties retaining foreign employees at the headquarters due to the lack of amenities in the city.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Greimel |first=Hans |date=May 6, 2013 |title=Dreary HQ city is a handicap in global glitz plan |work=[[Automotive News]] |url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130506/GLOBAL02/305069976/dreary-hq-city-is-a-handicap-in-global-glitz-plan#axzz2SrMwuTWn |url-status=dead |access-date=May 9, 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130616011434/http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20130506/GLOBAL02/305069976/dreary-hq-city-is-a-handicap-in-global-glitz-plan%23axzz2SrMwuTWn |archive-date=June 16, 2013}}</ref>

Surrounding the headquarters are the 14-story Toyota Technical Center and the Honsha plant (which was established in 1938). Toyota and its Toyota Group affiliates operate a total of 17 manufacturing facilities in Aichi Prefecture and a total of 32 plants in Japan.

Toyota also operates offices in [[Bunkyo, Tokyo]], and [[Nakamura-ku, Nagoya]].<ref name="Toyotaprofile" />{{primary source inline|date=December 2023}}

